This is the cage-rules.md file — the operator-facing system prompt injected into a sandboxed agent session, not code consumed by the crate's logic directly. It defines the behavioral contract for an LLM agent running inside `ctx-cage`'s sandbox: use native Read/Edit/Write/Grep tools directly on the real working tree (not a brokered `ctx-access` protocol), treat injected `.context/` summaries as authoritative navigation aids, verify work via `ctx-verify` rather than raw cargo commands, and respect environment-level boundaries (no network, masked secrets, read-only toolchain, no destructive git).

Key coupling: this text explicitly tells the agent to override any stale tool-contract docs it finds in the project (CLAUDE.md, specs mentioning `ctx-access`, task ids, brokered reads/writes) — so if those docs still describe the old contract, this file is the source of truth and wins. Any change to the actual sandbox tool surface (e.g. renaming `ctx-verify`, changing `.context/` update mechanics) must be mirrored here or the agent will be given false operating instructions. It's plain markdown with no executable logic — treat edits as prompt engineering, not code changes, and be careful with wording precision since this is parsed by an LLM, not a compiler.